{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868909/1930111801/0634.xml":{"full_text":"It Seems io Me\nB.HEWOOD MN\nWHENEVER anybody hints in all charity that some\none\u2019s eccentric opinions may be dismissed upon the\nground of his immaturity he will be informed that Han\nnibal crossed the Alps at an early age and that Napoleon\nwas going great guns long before he reached 30. And the\nyounger Pitt will also be mentioned.\nR. Halford Forster, \u201cRepresentative In America of Randolph\nChurchill,\u201d takes exception to a recent column concerning his chief and\nmisses only one of the traditional prodigies in his rebuttal.\nBut Mr. Foster misunderstood my objection to the lecture tour'nf\nthe tire-eating British schoolboy. It does not abash me at all to be\ninformed for the 100th time that William Pitt entered parliament at the\nage of 21. That, at least, leaves him two up on Churchill, minor, yet\neven so I have not the slightest wish to keep this glib youngster out\nof the house of commons. I merely expressed amazement that he\nshould be seriously received as a visiting lecturer on topics of Inter\nnational moment.\nSurely no one would maintain that sound grounding in world poli\ntics was ever made essential for a legislator in any land.\nNot Precisely a Mute Milton.\nI FI ND myself not much moved by the qualification of Randolph\nChurchill which his representative advances as peculiar. He\nspeaks of the lad as one \u201cwho has had the privilege of being with a\nfather who by his actions early in August, 1914, admittedly saved\nEurope.\u201d\nThe answer to that must be a blunt \u201cWho hasn\u2019t?\u201d The achieve\nments of Winston Churchill, the opinions of Winston Churchill, the\nremarkable attributes of Winston Churchill and Mr. Churchill's views\non this world and the next can hardly be a secret to any literate\nAmerican. Next to Lloyd George he has been the most articulate and\nprolific of all syndicated features originating in the British Isles.\nFor years it has been almost impossible to pick up an American\nnewspaper or magazine without finding something signed and dotted\nby the British statesman. Nor have I any wish to be captious about\nhis contributions. It is all good, lively stuff. Winston Churchill\nwrites at least two and a half times as well as our Mr. Coolidge, and\nat times he is very nearly as amusing as Will Rogers.\nWe Columnists Know.\nIT MIGHT be said that in all his narrative one sees life through a\nChurchill darkly, but, after all, who am I to adopt a censorious\nattitude toward those who make a maypole of the first person singular\nand dance around it?\nIt is interesting, of course, to learn that in August, 1914, Winston\nChurchill \u201cadmittedly saved Europe.\u201d Has Europe heard of it, and\nshouldn't that continent be tie first to know?\nPlain, Blunt and Frank.\nTHERE is no reason why men or women who come across the sea\nto give us lecture tours should also bear with them gifts of\nflattery. I hold it reasonable for them to like neither our women nor\nthe taller buildings. But if there, is too much suggestion of the mis\nsionary spirit in my provincial way I bridle. I am distressed if I get\nthe impression that fellow citizens of mine are going to box office\nwindows with things of value which they will presently exchange for\nbeads and bits of colored cloth.\nBritain Plays a Lone Hand.\nT\u2019hUS the educational motive of young Randolph Churchill is\nA hardly magnified in my eyes when R. Halford Forster, his rep\nresentative, writes to me, \u201cYou will remember, won\u2019t you, that for\nyears of the mud and blood In Flanders, until they were convoyed\nacross by the British fleet, there were quite a number bashing silver\ndollars one against the other whilst we (I happened to do four and a\nhalf very undistinguished years of war service) waited.\u201d\nIn this I seem to see the deft touch of British reticence, which\nshrinks as does the Mexican jumping bean. But I\u2019m all for British\nreticence. For the sake of Anglo-American relations I could wish for\neven more of it.\nA Six Months\u2019 Error.\nIV/T R. FORSTER informs me that I am incorrect in referring to\nAv A Randolph Churchill as 19. It seems that he is actually 191/2\nI am further Informed that he \u201cwas certainly not told to wash behind\nhis ears.\u201d\nAll of which leaves-me with the possibly parochial notion that\nthere are still things which are better ordered In the United States.\nAUTO ACCIDENT\nKILLS FORMER\nMILWAUKEEANS\nWalter J. Mack, 88 years old, and\nhis wife, Lois, 31 years old, for*\nmerly of Milwaukee were killed\nlate yesterday in an automobile\ncrash near Twig, Minn.\nThe Macks were camping in\nnorthern Wisconsin and were en\nroute to Duluth where they planned\nto spend Thanksgiving,\nHas Narrow Escape.\nGus Jeschinske, 710 Linden st.,\nescaped with minor injuries when a\nNorth Western train demolished his\nautomobile near his home.\nMrs. Lillian Smith, 45 years old,\n459 Twenty-ninth st., and Dorothy\nBickel, 14 years old, 461 Twenty\nninth st., were hurt when run down\nby an automobile at Vliet and\nTwenty-sixth sts. Emil Beer, 38\nyears old, 2637 W, Ulybourn st.,\nwas struck near his home. Oliver\nEimerman, 18 years old, 2572 N.\nEighth st., was bit at Center and\nNinth sts.\nKnocked Down by Auto.\nWhile riding a bicycle at Cass\nand Michigan sts., Nick Menis, 14\nyears old, 814 East Michigan st.,\nwas struck by an automobile.\nDELAY REALTY\nFIRM HEARING\nThe department of agriculture\nand markets has fixed next Tues\nday as the time for a hearing of\ncharges that the Milwaukee Build\ning and Development Co. used un\nfair methods of selling subdivision\nlots, especially by employing a\n\u2018free lot\u201d offer.\nThe date was set following a rul\ning yesterday by Circuit Judge Gus\ntave G. Gehrz, dissolving a re\nstraining order by which the com\npany had succeeded in temporarily\nblocking tl -\"\u2019lug.\nAttorney Tl. M. Orchard of the\nattorney general's staff agreed to a\ndelay of one week.\nFUNERAL RITES\nTHURSDAY FOR\nMRS. JENNINGS\nFuneral services for Mrs. Alice\nJennings, 79 years old, wife of\nThomas Jennings, pioneer lumber\nman, who died yesterday at her\nhome, 1305 West Wisconsin ave.,\nafter a long illness, will be held at\n9 a. m. Thursday in Gesu church.\nInterment will be in Holy Cross\ncemetery.\nMrs. Jennings was the mother of\nCivil Judge Francis J. Jennings and\nDavid V. Jennings, chief examiner,\nMilwaukee county civil service com\nmission.\nWith her family, Mr. Jennings\nmoved as a young girl from Peter\nboro, Canada, her birthplace, to\nNew London, Wis., where she was\nmarried in 1860. Mr. Jennings at\nthat time owned a lumber mill in\nNew London, and cleared forests\nalong the Wolf river.\nAfter Mr. Jennings retirement in\n1900 at Shawano, Wis., where he\nowned a lumber mill, the Jennings\nfamily moved to Milwaukee.\nMrs. Jennings belonged to the\nCatholic Order of Foresters and to\nthe Gesu church.\nOther survivors include seven\ndaughters, Sister Marietta, Kansas\nCity, Mo.; Mrs. W. H Page, Spo\nkane, Wash.; Mrs. Anne Marti\nneau, Mrs. P. F. Grant. Mrs. Joseph\nE. Tierney. Mrs. L. J Foley and\nMiss Aurelia Jennings, all of Mil\nwaukee, and another son, Dr. E. J.\nJennings, Spokane, Wash.\nFuneral Rites for\nCity Stationary\nEngineer Are Held\nFuneral services for R. C. Deck\nman, 67 years old. 481 Fifty-first\nst., for 23 years a stationary engi\nneer for the city and long time So\ncialist, who died Saturday, was held\nat 2 p. m. today at the Schmidt and\nBartelt funeral home. 5040 Vliet st.\nThe members of Exclesior lodge.\nNo. 20, of the Odd Fellows, of\nwhich Mr. Deekman was a mem\nber. officiated at the services.\nMr. Deckman is survived by his\nwidow. Mrs. Anna Deckman. a\nmember of the West Side Women\u2019s\nbranch of the Socialist party, a son.\nRobert, Jr., a grandson, and a sis\nter. Mrs. John Krueger, Waterford,\nWis.\nDisclose Treis Not Familiar With Book Suit\nJUDGE FOBBIDS\nFURTHER QUERY\nON KNOWLEDGE\nShow Treis Has Paid\nTaxes Only Two\nYears.\nThe mystery as to the Identity of\nJoseph A. Treis, who began the suit\nas a \u201ctaxpayer\u201d against the city to\nquestion the valadity of the public\nlibrary\u2019s contract for the purchase\nof books from Hampel\u2019s Book Shop,\nInc., 218 Wells st., was solved today\nwhen he appeared upon the witness\nstand in the court of Circuit Judge\nAugust E. Braun.\nTreis became a taxpayer two\nyears ago, he testified, when he\nbought his home at 353 Brady st.,\nand he is 38 years old.\nUnfamiliar with Matter.\nOn cross examination by Attorney\nWilliam F. Quick, who, with Joseph\nA. Padway, represents the Hampel\nconcern, Treis admitted that he had\nnot read the city charter, provisions\nwhich are referred to in his sworn\ncomplaint.\nFurther questions as to Treis\u2019\nknowledge and sources of informa\ntion concerning his allegations were\nshut off by Judge Braun on objec\ntion by the plaintiff\u2019s attorney, J.\nElmer Lehr.\nTells of Contract.\nThe history of book-buying con\ntracts was described in detail by\nM. S. Dudgeon, librarian of the pub\nlic library.\nThe incomplete offer of McClurg\nand Co., Chicago bookseller, and the\npartial offer of Des Forges and Co.,\ntogether with the complete offer of\nthe Hampel concern, all submitted\nprior to July 12, 1927, were de\nscribed by Dudgeon. The award to\nHampel\u2019s company was made Dec.\n12, 1927.\n100 WILL SEE\nSHIP LAUNCHING\nA delegation of 100 business men\nand public officials will go to Mani\ntowoc next Tuesday to attend the\nlaunching of the new twin-screw\ncarferry City of Milwaukee of the\nGrand Trunk Western Railroad Co.\nThe launching will take place in\nthe yards of the Manitowoc Ship\nbuilding corporation, which built the\ncarferry at a cost of $1,000,000.\nWilliam F. Eichfeld. president,\nAssociation of Commerce, will speak.\nSheehan Concedes\nStafford Victory\nJames P. Sheehan, Socialist can\ndidate for congress in the Fifth dis\ntrict, in the election Nov. 4, today\nconceded victory to his stalwart Re\npublican opponent, William H. Staf\nford, after the election commission\u2019s\nrecount showed a gain by Stafford\nof 150 votes in 39 precincts.\nMANY CLASSES\nOF MASONS TO\nHOLD REUNIONS\nMore classes of Wisconsin Con\nsistory 32nd degree Masons are\nholding reunion meetings in connec\ntion with the fall session of that\nbody in the Scottish Rite cathedral\nthis week than at any time in the\n70 years of the organization\u2019s exist\nence.\nReunions arranged for tomorrow\nare the Semper Paratus class, fall\nof 1801, at the home of Dr. C. E.\nAlbright at 6:30 p. m.; the fall class\nof 1905, at the Elks\u2019 club at 12 m.;\nthe Stand True class, fall of 1906,\nat the Schroeder hotel at 6 p. m.;\nthe fall class of 1908, at the Univer\nsity club at 5:30 p. m.; the spring\nclass of 1915, at the M. A. C. at\n6:30 p. in.; the Liberty class, fall of\n1917, at the M. A. C. on Wednesday\nevening; the Peace class, fall of\n1918, at the Elks\u2019 club at 6 p. m.;\nthe Sidney T. Smythe class, spring\nof 1923, at the Republican liotel at\n6 p. m.; the James M. Hayes class,\nspring of 1924. at the Elks\u2019 club at\n6 p. m.; the George H. Benzenberg\nclass, fall of 1925. at the Blatz ho\ntel at 6 p. m.; the W. C. Stone\nciass, spring of 1927, at the M. A.\nC. at 6:30 p. m.; the Trinity class,\nspring of 1930, at the Schroeder ho\ntel at 6 p. in.\nTwo Degree Teams.\nTwo degree teams will participate\nin the work at the Cathedral on\nWednesday. The 17th, 18th, 19th\n23rd and 21st degrees will be con\nferred.\nThirty-one Milwaukee and Wis\nconsin men late yesterday became\nnobles of the Mystic Shrine during\nthe fall ceremonial initiation at\nTripoli temple. 3000 Wisconsin ave.\nOfficers in Charge.\nTen officers of the temple, gar\nmented as Arabian nobles, put the\ncandidates through their paces.\nThey were Henry Petran, illustri\nous potentate: Arthur Novak, chief\nrabban: Adolph Hafner, assistant\nrabban; William Dittman, high\npriest and prophet; Henry F. Zarge,\nrecorder.\nGeorge Eller, first ceremonial\nmaster; Emory Krauthoofer, sec\nond ceremonial master: Dr. Earl\nEllsworth, third ceremonial master;\nWilliam Pietsch, captain of the\nguards, and Paul G. Pohle, outer\nguard.\nTHE MILWAUKEE LEADER, TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 18, 1930\nSIX WOMEN IN NEW CONGRESS\nB 72^^\nMl\n||gg|M\nHQk w\nBR is\nHL\n'*9^ I wk-\nThis sextet will comprise the\nfeminine contingent of the hon e\nof representatives in the new\ncongress. The women are, up\nper left, Mrs. Ruth Pratt, of New\nYork; upper right, Airs. Otis Win\ngo, of Arkansas; center, left to\nright, Mrs. Ruth Bryan Owen of\nCAMPAIGN BODY\nASKS RAWLEIGH,\nVITS TO APPEAR\nGeorge Vits, Manitowoc aluminum\ngoods manufacturer and Republi\ncan national committeeman, and\nW. T. Rawleigh, Fneeport, 111., man\nufacturer and contributor to pro\ngressive Republican campaign funds\nin Wisconsin, have been requested\nto appear before the legislative\ncampaign investigating committee\nmeeting here Thursday and in Mad\nison Friday and Saturday.\nNumerous other witnesses have\nbeen summoned for the two hear\nings by this committee authorized\nto investigate campaigns since 1924\nwith a view towards discovering\nviolations of. and making recom\nmendations for strengthening, the\ncorrupt practices act which governs\ncampaign practices and expendi\ntures.\nRep. Hubert H. Peavey, congress\nman from the 11th district, will\nappear either in Madison or Mil\nwaukee.\nSubpoenas for the Milwaukee\nmeeting have been issued for E. H.\nMiller, secretary of the Sheboygan\ncounty Republican club Roy E.\nReed, Ripon: William F. Kinsella,\nOliver E. Remey and O. H. Casper,\nMilwaukee.\nOLD INDUSTRIAL\nSCHOOL MAY BE\nCLUB FOR GIRLS\nHope that the buildings of the\nWisconsin Industrial SchooL. for\nGirls, 465 Lake drive, will be con\nverted into a dub for working girls,\nwhen the school is moved to its\nnew location near Oregon, Wis., was\nexpressed by Mrs. Elizabeth Pres\ncott, director of the school, in ad\ndressing the American Association\nof University Women yesterday at\nthe College Women\u2019s club.\nFive Youths Hurt\nPlaying Football\nThroughout City\nFootball brought injuries to five\nyouths in the Milwaukee district\nyesterday.\nEdward Evens, 15 years old, 1331\nSouth Fifteenth place, and Phillip\nPilek, 19 years old, 1908 West Ar\nthur ave., were slightly injured near\ntheir homes.\nRobert Lust, 21 years old. 143\nBrown st., and Roy Packard, 19\nyears old, 2047 Hubbard st., were\nhurt in a game at the Henry Clay\nschool in Whitefish Bay. Morris\nRapkin, 18 years old, 1805 Clarke\nst., a North Division High school\nstudent, was hurt in practice.\nRELEASE WIDOW\nOF OESTERREICH\n7 r rs. Walburga Oesterreich, 50\nyea.' old. yesterday was released\nwithout bond in Los Angeles.\nThe widow of Fred Oesterreich,\nformer Milwaukee apron manufac\nturer, of whose murder she had\nbeen accused, had been tried once\non that charge. The jury disagreed.\nThe court then instructed the\ninry to decide by Dec. 15 whether\nMrs. Oesterreich is to be retried or\nthe charges are to be dismissed.\nFlorida; Mrs. Katherine Langley,\nof Kentucky; Mrs. Florence P.\nKahn, of California; below, Mrs.\nEdith Nourse Rogers of Massa\nchusetts. Mrs. Ruth. Hanna Mc-\nCormick, of Illinois, and Mrs.\nPearl Oldfield, of Arkansas, are\nvoluntarily retiring as congress\nwomen.\nDETECTIVES FOR\nRURAL REGIONS,\nPLAN OF WOMEN\nWisconsin has an enviable repu\ntation for swift and sure justice in\nrepressing crime\u2014a reputation due\nlargely to well organized machin\nery in Milwaukee.\n\u201cWisconsin gets its men\u201d is a\nmagazine headline that may not\ndeserve to live if the state fails to\nfind and punish the men who have\nterrorized villages and small cities\nin 25 daylight bank robberies in\nthe last 12 months.\nThese statements were made\nyesterday by Miss Edith Fosrer,\nsecretary, committee on crime and\ncriminal justice, speaking before a\nmeeting of the Milwaukee Wom\nan\u2019s club.\n\u201cThe subcommittee on detection\nand apprehension of criminals is\nplanning some means of affording\nrural districts, villages and small\ncities a detective service compar\nable to that provided by the Mil\nwaukee police department detective\nbureau,\u201d said Miss Foster.\nREVIEW FINDS\nBUSINESS HAS\nNOT RECOVERED\nThe business revival which was\nsupposed to come this fall has not\narrived, according to the monthly\nreview of business of the Wiscon\nsin Bankshares corporation.\nInstead of gaining business\nreached a new low point in October.\nLess iron, steel and automobiles\nwere produced and the number of\nnew automobiles registered in Wis\nconsin was 4,772 against 8,415 for\nSeptember last year.\nDecline in Payrolls.\nFactory emplc; ::ent and pa^ oils\ndeclined. Price trends of farm\nproduce has been downward. Stock\nmarket values have dropped. Bonds\nhave slipped.\nThe review continues:\n\u201cIn The Annalist, Prof. Lionel D.\nEdie shows quite conclusively that\nbusiness has recovered from past\ndepressions despite relatively high\ninventories. Stocks that manufac\nturers and merchants are carrying\nnow are, in fact, not much below\nthose of a year ago.\n\u201cIt is the consumer who initiates\nthe train of events that pulls us out\nof depression.\nLike Former Slumps.\n\u201cSerious as the problems are that\nconfront the world, there is noth\ning in the situation that has not\nbeen met and overcome before, the\nreview points out, and the most\nimportant difference between 1921\nand 1930 lies in the soundness of\nour credit situation compared with\nthat of nine years ago.\u201d\nSeldom have there been better op\nportunities, both for income and ap\npreciation, than are to be found in\nthe bond market today, the survey\ndeclared.\nDentists to Hear\nDr. R. W. Bunting\nDr. Russell W. Bunting, Univer\ncity of Michigan, will speak at the\nmeeting of the Wisconsin Academy\nof Dentists, Dec. 3, in the Schroe\nder hotel.\nU.S. JURY FREES\nIST DEFENDANT\nIN STILL CASE\nThe first jury trial on the fall\ncalendar of criminal cases in fed\neral court was won by the defend\nant today when liquor charges\nagainst Joseph Kalinith, 7421 Be\nloit road, were dismissed.\nThe jury contended that Kalinith\nwas not guilty of operating the still\nin the basement of his home as was\ncharged by the government Testi\nmony during this trial showed that\nagents had unlatched the door to\nthe home by forcing open a milk\nchute.\nSix Receive Sentences.\nDefense testimony was to the ef\nfect that Kalinith\u2019s wife and a\nfriend had installed the still against\nhis wishes.\nThe verdict of not guilty was ft\nsealed one and was returned to Fed\neral Judge Geiger today.\nSix defendants were sentenced\nas follows:\nMike Steiner, 459 Third st., who\noperated a saloon at that place and\nwas charged with maintaining a\nnuisance, was sentenced, to six\nmonths and a fine of $250.\nMaglio Is Sentenced.\nJames Tullis, bartender, was fined\nSIOO and Leo Dries, proprietor of\nthe saloon, Fond du Lac, Wis., was\nsentenced to six months and a fine\nof S2OO imposed for maintaining a\ncommon nuisance.\nSal Maglid, owner of the former\nEast Side Palm Gardens. 495 Jeffer\nson st., who was charged with main\ntaining a common nuisance there,\nwas sentenced to six months in the\nhouse of correction and fined $250.\nClarence Michaels, owner, and\nJule Smith, bartender, who main\ntained a common nuisance in the\nsaloon at Appleton, Wis., were sen\ntenced, the owner receiving six\nmonths and S2OO while Smith paid\na fine of SIOO.\nTen Fail to Appear.\nTen defendants who were to have\nappeared before Judge Geiger on\nliquor cases failed to appear and\nconsequently bends totaling $5,000\nwere forfeited. Those who failed\nto appear and for whom warrants\nare out are:\nLuther Woodarg, 459 Third st.,\nand Catherine Jendrick, Cold Spring\nroad and Highway 10\u00b0; bonds\nSI,OOO\nSam Petropolous, 399 Twelfth st,\nbond SI,OOO.\nWarrants were returned on the\nfollowing:\nMax Rossman, IG3O Galena st.,\nbond SSOO.\nNell Warner. 830 Clybourn st.,\nbond SSOO.\nJoseph Marks, 126 Fifth st., no\nbond.\nSam Reichow, 1010 Cherry st.,\nbond SSOO.\nLon Flowers, 948 Kinnickinnic\nave., no bond.\nJack CoJahan, 204 Fourth st.,\nbond SI,OOO.\nBon Wolfson, 1200 Fiftieth st.,\nbond SSOO.\nIn the two days of the fall cal\nendar, 21 defandants have been im\nposed fines of $3,175 and terms in\nthe house of correction were 49\nmonths. Twelve cases were dis\nmissed and 10 defendants forfeited\nbonds for not appearing for trial.\nTo Hold Exam For\nMinimum Wage Job\nThe Milwaukee County Civil\nService commission has announced\nan examination for the position of\nminimum wage inspector to be con\nducted at 9 a. m. Dec. 1 at the\noffice of the commission, 470 Jef\nferson st.\nThe examination is opened to\nqaulified residents of Milwaukee\ncounty 21 years of age or over.\nThe position pays from $8 to $lO\na day.\nFIRST GIFTS IN\nJEWISH DRIVE\nTOTAL $50,000\nGifts donated by the Jewish\ndonors amounted to approximately\n$50,000 yesterday, according to\nNathan J. Gould, chairman of the\npublicity committee for the Fed\nerated Jewish Charity drive which\nwas initiated to raise $150,000 to\ncare for Milwaukee\u2019s unfortunate\nJews.\nThis amount is 10 per cent higher\nthan last year\u2019s initial gifts, A. L.\nSaltzstein, chairman of the initial\ngifts committee, rei>orted.\nPlan Luncheon Meet.\nThe 400 workers will meet in the\nSky room of the Plankinton hotel\nat a luncheon tomorrow to make\nfurther reports on the progress of\nthe drive, which will last 10 days.\nDr. S. M. Goldsmith, head of the\nJewish Social service of Chicago,\nwill speak.\nCharities to Be Aided.\nThe charities which will be aided\nby the fund are the Jewish Social\nService Assn., Mount Sinai hospi\ntal. the Jewish center, the Chil\ndren's Outing Assn., the Board of\nJewish Education, the Ladies\u2019 Re\nlief Sewing society, and Various\nnational agencies.\nNearly 2,000 persons were aided\nby the organization last year. Free\nservice was siven to 872 potients\nat Mount Sinia hospital at a cost\nof $31,109, and the Board of Jewish\nEducation maintained classes in\ntwo schools for nearly 400 children.\nMarshals in the drive are: Jos\neph G. baneman, Ben Nickoil. Hen\nry Eckstein, Ben Gill, Mrs. Aaron\nYaffe. Mrs. Michael Levin, and\nMrs. Sigmund Brachman. Max A.\nFreschi is treasurer of the drive.\nTHIS \u2018BENEFIT BALL\u2019 TO BE\nFOR CHARLIE, NOT AL BENSON\nBENEFIT BALL==\u00bb\nGIVEN FOR\nS II K R 1 F F\nChas. Reichenbach\nat NORTH AVENUE AUDITORIUM\n3114 NORTH AVENUt\nThurs., November 17th\nENTERTAINMENT\u2014REFRESHMENTS\nAdmission SI.OO per couple\nto be given Nov. 27 in the North\nSide auditorium \u2014at $1 a throw.\nThe tickets state plainly that it is\nReichenbach who is to be benefited,\nbut telephone sales are made by use\nof the word which has been potent\nmagic in Milwaukee county in past\nyears, \u201cthe sheriff.\u201d\nBenson has notified his friends he\nhas no connection with the benefit\ntor Charlie.\nEverybody is Invited to a benefit\nball for the sheriff.\nWhich sheriff, Al Benson, Social\nist, or his predecessor, Charlie Rei\nchenbach, conservative Republican?\nThat\u2019s the question, and you\u2019ll\nnever know listening to the invita\ntions coming from the solicitors,\nwho say they are speaking from the\nsheriff's office.\nThe benefit is for Charlie and is\nOFFICE SUPPLIES\nVALVED AT SIM\nTAKEN BY THIEF\nOffice supplies valued at SIOO\nwere reported stolen by the Central\nChemical Co., 611 South Water st.,\nlast night.\nA thief ripped off a pay station\ntelephone from a wall of the S.\nZuhrensky Co., 1415 South Second\nst.\nNiels Mikkelsen, 2623 West State\nst., had clothing valued at $125\nstolen from his home.\nSAFETY ISLES\nPROPOSED FOR\nCAPITAL DRIVE\nCity Engineer Joseph P. Schwada\nwas instructed to make a survey of\ncost of constructing safety isles on\nWest Capitol drive, from North\nRichards st. to North Twenty-sev\nenth st., by the common council late\nyesterday.\nNew Fire House.\nSchwada suggested that the isles\nbe constructed while the street Is\ntorn up for the laying of a 54-inch\nwater main.\nThe council approved transfer of\n$40,000 to the fire department build\ning fund for the erection of a new\nfire house at North Hopkins st.,\nnear Villard five.\nAid. Robert J. Landowski, non\npartisan, 13th ward, introduced a\nresolution directing David I. Mc-\nKeiia, commissioner, of public\nUpon presentation of this Ad to any sales person In either Bl\nWB store you ran P nrc,iase the following Items below whole- I\n9 sale cost. All items limited.\n29c WHISK BROOMS. 19c\nS 25c COLGATE\u2019S S\u25a0 14c |l\nJ 25c MENNEN\u2019S 13c i\nI 50cSANITARY NAPKINS. 19c\ni MES\u2019 SILK lO SE 10c I\nII BABY BOOTIES\"^ II\nI SOAP m 9c I\nI WORK PANTS 79c\nOVERALLS 79c I\nI MATTRESS COVERS. 79c\nI BLEAeWEB FLANNEL.9^cII\nI FRAMED PICTORES 29c I\nII 5c PARLOR MATCHES. 2c\nI CBPS\u2014SAUCERS 9c\nI 10c TOILET PAPER SSS 5c I\n50c XMAS CARDS.=,.29c\n3 DIPHTHERIA\nCASES FOUND\nIN ONE CLASS\nThree cases of diphtheria and\nfive cnrrie;'\" of diphtheria germs\nhave been discovered in one class\nroom of a parochial school on :he\nsouth side this week, it was an\nnounced by Dr. M. R. French, medi\ncal director of the bureau of com\nmunicable disease of the health de\npartment today.\nThe children afflicted with the\ndisease and those found to be car\nriers have been quarantined and\ndaily examinations are being made\nin the class rooms.\nDr. French Attributes the spread\nof the disease hero to the failure\nof the parents of children In this\nschool to co-operate in the city\nhealth campaign against diphtheria,\nand also of the failure of the school\nauthorities to keep an accurate rec\nord of the absent children.\nLast week a child was absent four\ndays before school made note\nof his abgci.ee and then it was\n\u25a0found that the child had been ill\nwith diphtheria during the period\nand had received no medical treat\nment.\nworks, to determine the cause of\nthe faulty ventilation in the public\nsafety building.\nWould Amend City Code.\nAmendment of the city code to\npermit peddlers on regular routes\nto leave horses untied while they\nare making deliveries, unless they\nare vicious, was introduced by Aid\nSamuel Sores, non-partisan, Sixth\nward.\nPage Two","height":"29013","width":"21273"}}
